Use conditional compilation directives in `MauiProgram.cs` to register platform-specific implementations:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which is already platform-filtered by the default `.csproj` settings). This ensures only the relevant type compiles per target, so it won't break on any platform.

**Alternative** — if you prefer avoiding `#if` directives, use partial classes or the `Platforms/` folder convention with a shared registration helper per platform, but the approach above is the most common and straightforward.
